[Student "S"]
{You open 1\S and partner jumps to 3\S.

Wow. It looks like you might have a great fit. You bid 4NT and partner responds 5\H.

Partner shows 2 Aces so you bid 6\S.

South plays 6\S. West leads the \DK.

<b>South plays 6\S. West leads the \DK.</b>

Losers: \S 1? : \H 1 : \D 0 : \C 0 : Total = 2?

If trumps don't split 3-2 you will definitely go down 1, so assume they do split. You could finesse East once in \Hs, or use a ruffing finesse on West, but the cleanest approach is just to ruff two \Hs in dummy. Of course you must do this before you pull trumps.

Win the \DA in dummy. Play the \HQ to the \HA and ruff the \H10 with dummy's \S8. Play the \S5 to your \SA and ruff the \HJ with dummy's \S9.

Return to your hand with a \C and pull another round of trumps with your \SK. Leaving the master trump out start playing \C winners. Someone may ruff with their master trump but that's the only trick they will get.

It was very bold to bid this slam and North/South were fortunate to find a distribution where it could be made.

But that would have been all for nothing if South had not found the PLAN to make it.}
[Play "W"]DK

